# Approach
To calculate the difference between the two times, we need to first convert them to "integer-minutes", so that the 24h-time is being represented by minutes of the day between 0 and 1440 (24*60).
Therefore I use StringToMinutes, which adds up the chars int the string representing the hours and minutes into seperate integers and returns their sum.

The actual problemsolving algorithm works as follows:
As long as we can add 60 (minutes) to the current Time and its still smaller or equals to the correct time we do so. If its not possible anymore we continue to do so with 15, 5 and 1. That way we ensure that the minimal number of operations is used, since we add the highest numbers as long as its possible and then switch to the smaller ones.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int convertTime(String current, String correct) {

        int curTime=StringToMinute(current);
        int corTime=StringToMinute(correct);
        int counter=0;

        while(curTime+60<=corTime){
            curTime+=60;
            counter++;
        }
        while(curTime+15<=corTime){
            curTime+=15;
            counter++;
        }
        while(curTime+5<=corTime){
            curTime+=5;
            counter++;
        }
        while(curTime+1<=corTime){
            curTime+=1;
            counter++;
        }

        return counter;
    }

    public int StringToMinute(String st){
        int min=0;
        int hours=0;

        //the "  -'0'  " is needed since .charAt(i) would only return the Unicode points for the numbers "1, 2, 3" and so on
       hours+=(st.charAt(0)-'0')*10+st.charAt(1)-'0';

       min+=(st.charAt(3)-'0')*10+(st.charAt(4)-'0');

        return min+hours*60;
    }
}
```

