/*

      Pre-Requisites :--> Prefix Sum + Binary Search

      Logic in a Nutshell :--> Actually in these type of questions , where the optimal answer is dependent on two distinct entities ,

                               We used to fix one entity and try to change ( increment / decrement ) its value ; and then figure out what 

                               is the impact of the first operation on the second entity.


                Maybe , it sounds not so good , but analyzing the question you can easily get that Our answer depends on 

                 (1) Number of full flowers --> (num_full*fullValue)  --> val1
                 (2) Minimum value of Incomplete flower --> (min_incomp*partialValue)  --> val2


               And the optimal answer will be the maxValue from any of the combinations of these two entity 

               [ e.g :- 2 full flower + 3 partial flower
                        4 full flower + 1 partial flower
                        1 full flower + 3 partial flower ]


      Approach :-->  But how can we determine which valid combination fetchs us our desired output.

                     For these we have to make some basic but important observations ........


                    Observation(1) -->  We are given with fixed value of newFlowers (Let us consider it K) . Now we can use atmost K flowers.

                         So how can we use minimum number of newFlowers and get maximum number of full flowers( whose value >= taregt) ???

                         So obviously , we have to pick the Maximum valued flowers and try to put extra flowers till flowers[i]!=target.

            [ E.g :- flowers [2,4,6,7,9] , newFlowers = 5 , fullValue = 10 ---> Now we pick the flowers[4]=9 and use 1 flower .......]


                   Observation(2) --> Now after we are done with the first part ( Current number of full flowers that we can achieve using atmost newFlowers amount of flowers )       

                   After using certain amount of flowers in making certain amount of flowers "full" , let us say we have "rest" amount of newFlowers , we have to decide what we can do further with these amount of flowers.

                   So , for these we have to look at the definition of

                "sumofbeauty" --> "# of full flowers * fullVal " + " Minimum valued incomplete flower * partialVal "


                So it is not that we can make one flower[i] so big with "rest" flowers , as the minimum incomplete flowers[i] remains the same and it will not increment our result that much.

                Well ,we have to evenly distribute the "rest" flowers to all of the incomplete flowers and pick the Minimum one.

                wait wait , so as a whole we have to maximize the minimum flowers[i] --> bang on !!! Here comes the approach of Binary Search.

                Finally , we have to fix the value of the incomplete flowers [ which have flowers[i] < target ] to "mid" and check whether all the incomplete flowers can reach to the "mid" value and if yes then increment the value properly.   

