If you follow the aforementioned post, you may write your own version of binary search like mine:

```c++
// Binary Search 
// Time: O(nlogn)
// Space: O(n)

class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumBeauty(vector<int>& flowers, long long newFlowers, int target, int full, int partial) {
        const long long n = flowers.size();
        std::sort(flowers.begin(), flowers.end());
        std::vector<long long> costs(n, 0);
        // special case 1: all gardens are already complete
        if(flowers[0] >= target){
            return full * n;
        }
        flowers[0] = std::min(flowers[0], target); // cap it
        long long last_partial = 0;
        for(long long i = 1; i < n; ++i){
            if(flowers[i] >= target){
                flowers[i] = target;
            } else{
                last_partial = i;
            }
            costs[i] = costs[i - 1] + (flowers[i] - flowers[i - 1]) * i;
        }
        // special case 2: all gardens can be complete
        if(costs.back() + n * (target - flowers.back()) <= newFlowers){
            return std::max(full * n, full * (n - 1) + partial * static_cast<long long>(target - 1));
        }
        long long res = 0;
        for(auto first_complete = last_partial + 1; first_complete >= 0; --first_complete){
            newFlowers -= first_complete == n ? 0 : (target - flowers[first_complete]);
            if(newFlowers < 0){
                break;
            }
            // try to fill the first [0, first_complete) gardens to their maximum partial 
            const auto it = std::upper_bound(costs.begin(), costs.begin() + first_complete, newFlowers);
            const auto extra = (newFlowers - *(it - 1)) / (it - costs.begin());
            res = std::max(res, full * (n - first_complete) + partial * (extra + flowers[it - costs.begin() - 1]));
        }
        return res;

    }
};
```

Well, this is neat, and efficient enough with `O(nlogn)` complexity. And I would say this suffices for you to ace the Leetcode contest and any techinical interviews.

But wait a minute, just like me, you come across some other posts about two-pointer solutions and you want to optimize your code further! Unfortunately, as for now, these top posts about two-pointers solutions are not well written (in my opinion), and you don't want to spend a whole lot of time reading and understanding their pieces of code.

Don't fret, from binary search to two pointers, there's only a very small step forward. And that's exactly what I'm going to write about.

First, let's take a look at the code (or the binary-search solution) above, and you may have already noticed:

**When we iterate over `first_complete` and then do the binary search to find the maximal `it` for each `first_complete`, as `first_complete` decreases, `it` can never increase as `newFlowers` always decrease.** 

```c++
const auto it = std::upper_bound(costs.begin(), costs.begin() + first_complete, newFlowers);
```

This is because as we make more gardens complete, we have fewer new flowers to optimize the first several incomplete gardens. Quite intutive.

Then, to utilize this observation, instead of doing binary search each time, we may simply use another variable `best_effort` to **remember** the last position of `it` and decrement it all the time, which is the second pointer we need! (The first pointer is `first_complete` of course.) 

Therefore, with this key observation, to make the step forward from binary search to two pointers, you don't need to make much modification to your code at all! And for your reference, you can see that most of my code is **the same**:

```c++
// Sort + Two Pointers
// Time: O(nlogn)
// Space: O(n)

class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumBeauty(vector<int>& flowers, long long newFlowers, int target, int full, int partial) {
        const long long n = flowers.size();
        std::sort(flowers.begin(), flowers.end());
        std::vector<long long> costs(n, 0);
        // special case 1: all gardens are already complete
        if(flowers[0] >= target){
            return full * n;
        }
        flowers[0] = std::min(flowers[0], target); // cap it
        long long last_partial = 0;
        for(long long i = 1; i < n; ++i){
            if(flowers[i] >= target){
                flowers[i] = target;
            } else{
                last_partial = i;
            }
            costs[i] = costs[i - 1] + (flowers[i] - flowers[i - 1]) * i;
        }
        // special case 2: all gardens can be complete
        if(costs.back() + n * (target - flowers.back()) <= newFlowers){
            return std::max(full * n, full * (n - 1) + partial * static_cast<long long>(target - 1));
        }
        long long res = 0;
		// --- ALL code above is the same as the binary-search solution --- //
        for(auto first_complete = last_partial + 1, best_effort = last_partial; first_complete >= 0; --first_complete){
            newFlowers -= first_complete == n ? 0 : (target - flowers[first_complete]);
            if(newFlowers < 0){
                break;
            }
            best_effort = std::min(best_effort, first_complete - 1);
            // try to fill the first [0, first_complete) gardens to their maximum partial 
			// -> instead of binary search, we use another pointer here
            while(best_effort >= 0 && costs[best_effort] > newFlowers){
                --best_effort;
            }
            // we can only maximize [0, best_effort] gardens
            const auto extra = (newFlowers - costs[best_effort]) / (best_effort + 1);
            res = std::max(res, full * (n - first_complete) + partial * (extra + flowers[best_effort]));
        }
        return res;

    }
};
