solutions.content:
The goal is to find the maximum beauty score. However, neither maximizing complete gardens nor maximizing the minimum number of flowers of incomplete gardens yield the optimum. Thus one might need to go through most possible cases and get the largest one.

One idea is to gradually make near-complete gardens full (and we know the "full" score), and find the largest "partial" score from the remaining gardens. If we want to maximize the total score given that we first make `k` gardens full, we greedily choose `k` incomplete gardens that are nearest to `target` size, and hence we have most quota to maximize partial score. To greedily make gardens full, we sort the array and make the nearest-to-target one full in order.

The remaining part is to compute partial score given that `k` gardens are complete. To achieve this, we first construct a prefix sum table of the sorted array, and then we can compute "the flower needed to fill the 0-th to `i`-th garden up to `t`" by `t * (i+1) - presum[i]`. The goal is to find the largest `t`, where `t` is within the interval `[min(flowers), target - 1]`. We can use binary search to find the optimal `t`, and for fixed `t`, we can perform another binary search on `flowers[0:n-k]` to get the maximum index `i` where `flowers[i] <= t`, which is the largest garden we need to fill up to `t`. The following example illustrates the process:

```
k=2
quota=8
target=10
t: binary search through [1, 9]
  0|x         |    1
  1|xx        |    3
  2|xxx       |    6
  3|xxx       |    9
  4|xxxxx     |    14
  5|xxxxxxoooo|    20
  6|xxxxxxxxoo|    28
======================================
t=5
  0|xoooo|    |    1
  1|xxoo |    |    3
  2|xxxo |    |    6
  3|xxxo |    |    9
->4|xxxxx|    |    14    5*(4+1)-14=11 (>8)
  5|xxxxxxoooo|    20
  6|xxxxxxxxoo|    28
======================================
t=4
  0|xooo|     |    1
  1|xxoo|     |    3
  2|xxxo|     |    6
->3|xxxo|     |    9     4*(3+1)-9=7 (<=8)
  4|xxxxx     |    14    
  5|xxxxxxoooo|    20
  6|xxxxxxxxoo|    28
======================================
=>score(k=2) = full * k + partial * t
             = full * 2 + partial * 4
```
We iterate through all possible `k`-s, and the maximum score ever computed is our answer.


The following is the C++ code of this problem. Let `n` be the size of the `flowers` vector, and `t` be the numerical value of `target`, then the total time completity is `O(n (log t) (log n))`: each binary search over all possible partial points requires another nested binary search over the `flowers` array (in `upper_bound(flowers.begin(), flowers.begin() + i + 1, c)`), hence taking `O((log t) (log n))` per searching operation. The space complexity is `O(n)`, for building a prefix sum table.
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumBeauty(vector<int>& flowers, long long newFlowers, int target, int full, int partial) {
        int n = flowers.size();
        std::sort(flowers.begin(), flowers.end());

        // construct prefix sum table
        vector<long long> presum(1, flowers[0]);
        for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) presum.push_back(presum.back() + flowers[i]);

        // for each iteration, use binary search to find the largest
        // partial point of [0, i] given that [i+1, n) can be completed
        long long ans = 0, avfl = newFlowers;
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0 && avfl > 0; --i) {
            if (flowers[i] >= target) continue; 

            // largest possible partial weight 
            // must fall between [flowers[0], target - 1]
            int l = flowers[0], r = target - 1;
            while (l < r) {
                int c = l + (r-l+1)/2;
                int j = distance(flowers.begin(), prev(upper_bound(flowers.begin(), flowers.begin() + i + 1, c)));
                if (avfl < (long long)c * (j+1) - presum[j]) r = c-1;
                else l = c;
            }
            // beauty score of [0, i] incomplete + [i+1, n) complete 
            // = full * (n-i-1) + partial * maxPartialWeight
            ans = std::max(ans, (long long)full * (n-1-i) + (long long)partial * l);
            avfl -= target - flowers[i];
        }
        // all-complete case
        if (avfl >= 0) ans = std::max(ans, (long long)full * n);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

