# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This is a frequency-related problem, so we'll use a map data structure to solve it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
As we can observe that there's only 2 possible outputs:-
1. If the frequency is equal to 1 then task can't be performed so we will return -1.
2. If the frequency is greater than 1 then tasks can be performed and with two sub possibilies:-
    a. If the frequency is divisible by 3 then number of rounds required will be task's frequency/3.
    b. If the frequency is not divisible by 3 then number of rounds required will be task's (frequency/3)+1, as 1 or 2 tasks will be remaining in last and can be shifted with other tasks using one more round.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(n)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: `O(n)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumRounds(vector<int>& tasks) {

        int rounds = 0;

        // creating and initializing the map
        unordered_map<int, int> m;
        for(int i=0; i<tasks.size(); i++){
            m[tasks[i]]++;
        }

        for(auto i:m){
            // when no of tasks with same level is only 1
            if(i.second == 1){
                return -1;
            }

            // when no of tasks with same level is more than 1
            else{

                // when no of tasks with same level is divisible by 3
                if(i.second%3 == 0){
                    rounds += (i.second/3);
                }

                // when no of tasks with same level is remaining 1 or 2 in last, will add 1 more to round
                else if(i.second%3 == 1 || i.second%3 == 2){
                    rounds += (i.second/3)+1;
                }
            }
        }

        return rounds;
    }
};
```

