solutions.content:
##### Data Structure
Use ordered map, also called tree map, to store all the intervals.
The map has key=right and value=left. 
Using `right` as key is helpful for later binary search by calling lower_bound()
Another int value to store the total count

##### Algorithm
1. Binary search to find the closest intervals by `left`
2. Check if the found interval has intersection with new segment `[left, right]`
3. Cover the new segment by extending the left margin (also increasing the `count` in the mean time)
4. If there is still some segment not covered, repeat 2~4 for next iteration
5. After the iteration if there is still some segment not covered, add it into the tree map

##### C++
```
class CountIntervals {
public:
    CountIntervals() {

    }

    void add(int left, int right) {
        auto it = m.lower_bound(left);

        while (it != m.end() && left <= right) {
            auto &sl = it->second; // segment left
            auto &sr = it->first;  // segment right

            if (right < sl) { // no intersection
                break;
            }

            // extend left margin to cover the left part of new sement
            if (left < sl) {
                cnt += sl - left;
                sl = left;
            }

            // move left to the un-covered part for next iteration
            left = min(sr, right)+1;

            ++it;
        }

        if (left <= right) {
            cnt += right-left+1;
            m[right] = left;
        }
    }

    int count() {
        return cnt;
    }

private:
    map<int, int> m; // right -> left
    int cnt = 0;
};
```

