solutions.content:
This question uses components of https://leetcode.com/problems/insert-interval/.
However there is one difference. "Insert Interval" asks us to insert only one element. So I used a stack, and inserted. And it worked. Using a stack is O(n)
However doing same in this question leads to Time Limit Exceeded.

An alternative to using stack is using a Tree data structure.
Why? Because tree will help me do binary search in O(log n) time. So I can find any interval or my place among intervals in O(log n).
Functions I will use are floor() and ceiling(). Please read about floor() and ceiling() here: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/TreeSet.html.

Assumption: I will sort all intervals using "start".

Insertion steps for newInterval:
1. Datastructure: TreeSet. 
1. find floor() value for newInterval
	a. is previous mergeable into me? (previous.end >= newInterval.start)? 
	b. YES: then remove previous and merge into newInterval.
2. now I may merge intervals coming after me
	a. for each interval after me
		- is next mergable into me?
		- YES: remove next and merge it into newInterval
3. Since all the elements mergeable into me are merged, just insert me into Tree.

Code has two classes
class Interval - holds start, end, length, and has functions isMergeable() and merge().
class Solution - holds treeset, add() and count().

Interval class
```
class Interval implements Comparable<Interval> {
    int start;
    int end;
    int len;
    public Interval(int start, int end) {
        this.start = start;
        this.end = end;
        this.len = end - start + 1;
    }

    public void merge(Interval other) {
        start = Integer.min(start, other.start);
        end = Integer.max(end, other.end);
        len = end - start + 1;
    }

    public boolean isMergable(Interval other) {
        return (start <= other.start && other.start <= end) 
            || (start <= other.end && other.end <= end) 
            || (other.start <= start && end <= other.end);
    }

    public int compareTo(Interval other) {
        if(start == other.start) {
            return end - other.end;
        } else {
            return start - other.start;
        }
    }
}
```

And the solution class
```
class CountIntervals {
    TreeSet<Interval> ts = new TreeSet();
    int count = 0;

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        Interval newInterval = new Interval(left, right);

        // I may get merged into previous interval if my start < previous' end.
        Interval prev = ts.floor(newInterval);
        if(prev != null && newInterval.isMergable(prev)) {
            count -= prev.len;
            ts.remove(prev);
            newInterval.merge(prev);
        }

        // I may get merged into next interval(s) if my end > their start.
        while(true) {
            Interval next = ts.ceiling(newInterval);
            if(next != null && newInterval.isMergable(next)) {
                count -= next.len;
                ts.remove(next);
                newInterval.merge(next);
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }

        ts.add(newInterval);
        count += newInterval.len;   
    }

    public int count() {
        return count;
    }
}
```

Now what is effective time complexity for each insertion?
It is O(log n) for floor(), ceiling(), remove() and insert().
But notice the infinite while loop - it runs for all elements after my start, that are mergeable into me. In worst case, that will happen to all the n elements present in Tree. 
So for insertion, worst case time complexity is O(n log n).

Remember that using stack has time complexity O(n)
This is worse than using a stack. However remember that "big O" time complexity only tells about worst case and cannot be always used to judge the best solution.

