solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

Use TreeMap (Balanced Binary Search Tree) to track every interval, and maintain order.

When "add(left, right)" causes overlap with existing intervals, remove every interval "covered" by [left,right], and add [left,right] into the TreeMap.

I am trying to make code as memorizable and easy to understand as possible.

There are many cases in this problem.
- Overlap between existing and new intervals
- The new interval just overlaps (but does not totally cover) some existing intervals.


Converge some cases to some easily-explainable steps, **easy to explain in interview**.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

In some solutions, in TreeMap, key is left edge, value is right edge of interval. Then there are many corner cases.
In my solution, in TreeMap, key is edge of interval (either left or right), value is Boolean (false means left edge, true means right edge).

```
TreeMap<Integer, Boolean> edges;

// true -- right edge
// false -- left edge
// If add(3,5), then the map has (3,false), (6,true)
// range [3,6) -- left included, right not included

// Use "Example 1" in the description
// ["CountIntervals", "add", "add", "count", "add", "count"]
// [[], [2, 3], [7, 10], [], [5, 8], []]
// 1. add 2,3
// edges: (2,false), (4,true)
// 2. add 7,10
// edges: (2,false), (4,true), (7,false), (11, true)
// 3. add 5,8 -- handle overlap
// edges: (2,false), (4,true), (5,false), (11, true)
```

How to handle overlap?

## Step 1
![code1.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/378188b2-5d0d-457b-9ca8-111bb624043d_1677472560.4769201.jpeg)
In this picture,
- If `left` is inside one existing interval, **extend** `left` to the left edge of the interval.
- If `right` is inside one existing interval, same, **extend** `right` to the right edge of the interval.
Then every interval which overlaps with `[left,right]` is **totally covered** by `[left,right]` now.

![code2.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c466c59a-3677-47df-ae8e-e2f7cf4ac02a_1677473888.111718.jpeg)

## Step 2
Remove every interval covered by `[left,right]` from TreeMap, also update `count0` (see in code).

## Step 3
Add interval `[left,right]` to TreeMap, and also update `count0`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`void add(left,right)` is amortized $$O(log(n))$$
`int count()` is $$O(1)$$


- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
import java.util.SortedMap;

class CountIntervals {

    TreeMap<Integer, Boolean> edges;
    int count0 = 0;

    public CountIntervals() {
        edges = new TreeMap<>();
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        ++right; // right not included

        // $left can be inside one existing interval
        // Extend $left!
        Integer a = edges.floorKey(left);
        if (a!=null) {
            if (!edges.get(a)) {
                // left edge
                left = a;
            } else {
                // right edge
                if (left == a) {
                    left = edges.lowerKey(a);
                }
            }
        }

        // $right can be inside one existing interval
        // Extend $right!
        Integer b = edges.ceilingKey(right);
        if (b!=null) {
            if (edges.get(b)) {
                // right edge
                right = b;
            } else {
                // left edge
                if (right == b) {
                    right = edges.higherKey(b);
                }
            }
        }

        // remove everything between a, b (include a,b)
        SortedMap<Integer, Boolean> submap = 
            edges.headMap(right,true).tailMap(left,true);

        int curr = -12345;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Boolean> e : submap.entrySet()) {
            if (e.getValue()) {
                count0 -= (e.getKey()-curr);
            } else {
                curr = e.getKey();
            }
        }
        submap.clear();

        // Insert this interval
        edges.put(left, false);
        edges.put(right, true);
        count0 += (right-left);
    }

    public int count() {
        return count0;
    }
}

/**
