# Intuition
As there are 10^9 integers that could be in intervals, it is infeasible to count which integers are in intervals. 
Intuitively, a List of intervals should be kept. The intervals should be ordered and non-overlapping to allow for quickly checking whether a new interval overlaps with any existing intervals.
Counting of integers can be avoided by updating a counter variable whenever a new interval is added.

# Approach
`intervals` is a List of tuples containing the left and right bound of any interval. `k` stores the current number of integers in intervals.

## Adding a new Interval

The position `index` to insert a (new interval `toAdd`) can be determined by a Binary Search in `intervals`. Before inserting the interval, a few things should be considered:
- If there are intervals completely within `toAdd`, those shall be removed from `intervals`. Those intervals may be found in `intervals` directly after `index`.
- If there is an interval partially overlapping with `toAdd`, that inverval may be removed after adjusting `toAdd` to contain all integers contained in that interval. There can be only two such intervals (one before and one after `toAdd`), as intervals in `intervals` are non-overlapping.
- If `toAdd` is completely within another interval, it must not be added to intervals. That interval could be found at `index - 1`.

`k` needs to be adjusted whenever an interval is removed from or added to `intervals`.

## Count
Simply return `k`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
In a worst case, $$O(n ^2)$$ for adding new intervals. The Binary Search takes $$O(\log (n))$$ time. The removal of intervals takes $$O(n^2)$$ time in a worst case, as there may be $$n$$ fully overlapping intervals to be removed, and removing from an $$n$$ long List may take $$O(n)$$ time. However, it should be noted that the average case will be far better, as the removal of many intervals improves performance on future calls to `Add` by shortening the List of intervals.
In average, there will be less than one removal of fully overlapping intervals (as only one interval is added per call to `Add`, no more than one can be removed in average), resulting in $$O(n)$$ time for removals. 
Therefore, in an average case: 
    - $$O(n)$$ for`Add`
    - $$O(1)$$ for `Count`

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$, as there may be $$n$$ intervals that need to be stored in a List.

# Code
```
public class CountIntervals {
    List<(int start, int end)> intervals = new List<(int, int)>();
    int k = 0;
    public CountIntervals() {

    }    
    public void Add(int left, int right) {
        (int start, int end) toAdd = (left, right); //the interval we wish to insert

        //find index of first interval starting at or after the interval to add
        var index = intervals.BinarySearch((left, right));
        if (index < 0) index = ~index;

        //find overlapping intervals starting after toAdd
        for(int i = index; i < intervals.Count && intervals[i].start <= right; i++)
        {
            if(intervals[i].end <= right)
            {
                //intervals[i] is completely within toAdd, therefore it can be removed
                k -= intervals[i].end - intervals[i].start + 1; //adjust k for removed interval
                intervals.RemoveAt(i--);
            }
            else if(intervals[i].start <= right)
            {
                //intervals[i] partially overlaps with toAdd, therefore it can be removed                
                k -= intervals[i].end - intervals[i].start + 1; //adjust k for removed interval
                toAdd = (left, intervals[i].end);       //adjust to incorporate all of the removed interval
                intervals.RemoveAt(i--);
            }
        }

        //if this interval is not the first interval, a previous interval may overlap
        if(index > 0)
        {
            if(intervals[index - 1].end >= toAdd.end)
            {
                //the previous interval completely contains toAdd, therefore do nothing
            }
            else
            {
                if(intervals[index - 1].end >= toAdd.start)
                {
                    //the previous interval overlaps partially with toAdd
                    //change previous interval to incorporate all of toAdd
                    k += toAdd.end - intervals[index - 1].end;
                    intervals[index - 1] = (intervals[index - 1].start, toAdd.end);
                }
                else
                {
                    //the previous interval does not overlap with toAdd
                    intervals.Insert(index, toAdd);
                    k += toAdd.end - toAdd.start + 1;
                }
            }
        }
        else
        {
            //no previous interval to overlap with toAdd
            intervals.Insert(index, toAdd);
            k += toAdd.end - toAdd.start + 1;
        }
    }

    public int Count() {
        return k;
    }
}

