# Intuition
We can calculate count of integers (size of interval) during `add` operation. So, let's keep all not overlapping intervals and merge it with new interval in the `add` operation.
For proper `count`calculation duting `merger` interval we do the following:
`count -= size (existing interval)` and then `count += size(merged interval)`.

The most tricky part is to keep intevals in `TreeMap` for quick access by start interval and calculating overlaps because new interval may overlap from `0` to `n` interval from left, rigth and in the midle of `left` and `right` parameters of `add` method.

# Approach
Remove all intevals from left for new inteval and merge.
Remove all interval from right for new interval and merge.

Put merged inteval to the collection.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `avg O(logn)`, `O(nlogn)` in the worst case becase we have to remove all `n-1` intervals in case of adding inteval that overlap all existing.
- Space complexity: `O(n)` in the forst case

# Code
```
class CountIntervals {
    private int count;
    private final TreeMap<Integer, Integer> ranges = new TreeMap<>();

    public CountIntervals() {}

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        if (isFullContains(left, right)) return;

        var leftEntry = ranges.floorEntry(left);
        while (leftEntry != null && leftEntry.getValue() >= left) {
            removeByStart(leftEntry.getKey());

            left = Math.min(left, leftEntry.getKey());
            right = Math.max(right, leftEntry.getValue());

            leftEntry = ranges.floorEntry(left);
        }

        var rightEntry = ranges.ceilingEntry(left);
        while (rightEntry != null && rightEntry.getKey() <= right) {    
            removeByStart(rightEntry.getKey());

            left = Math.min(left, rightEntry.getKey());
            right = Math.max(right, rightEntry.getValue());

            rightEntry = ranges.ceilingEntry(left);
        }

        ranges.put(left, right);
        count += size(left, right);
    }

    public int count() {
        return count;
    }

    private boolean isFullContains(int left, int right) {
        var leftEntry = ranges.floorEntry(left);
        return leftEntry != null && right <= leftEntry.getValue();
    }

    private void removeByStart(int start) {
        int end = ranges.remove(start);
        count -= size(start, end);
    }

    private static int size(int a, int b) {
        return b - a + 1;
    }
}

