solutions.content:
**Approach:**

1. Using merge intervals and sorted list. Here this will give TLE, since the TC is O(1e5 ^ 5)
2. Using Fenwick/Segmented Tree, but a huge memory would be required. MC: O(2 * 1e9 + 1).
3. Using TreeMap/BST. The following solution is based on this approach.


**Java Solution:**

```
class CountIntervals {
    TreeMap<Integer, Integer> map;
    int cnt;

    public CountIntervals() {
        map = new TreeMap<Integer, Integer>();
        cnt=0;
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> m;
        while(!map.isEmpty() && (m = map.floorEntry(left)) != null && left <= m.getValue() && right >= m.getKey()) {
            cnt -= m.getValue() - m.getKey() + 1;
            left = Math.min(left, m.getKey());
            right = Math.max(right, m.getValue());
            map.remove(m.getKey());
        }
        while(!map.isEmpty() && (m = map.ceilingEntry(left)) != null && left <= m.getValue() && right >= m.getKey()) {
            cnt -= m.getValue() - m.getKey() + 1;
            left = Math.min(left, m.getKey());
            right = Math.max(right, m.getValue());
            map.remove(m.getKey());
        }
        map.put(left, right);
        cnt += right - left + 1;
    }

    public int count() {
        return cnt;
    }
}
```

**Time Complexity**: O(n log n), where n=no.of add() calls
**Space Complexity**: O(n)

