# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I first used a segment tree to solve this problem. However, the test cases are not randomized and therefore the segment tree becomes unbalanced (i.e. every addition strictly decreases or increases). Therefore, an AVL type structure to automatically rotate the tree is required (or you can code your own rotation function if you want but that's far too much work for me)


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Save all intervals in a tree and keep a total sum count of all the interval lengths added. Ensure the tree adds intervals in proper order and decrease interval sizes as needed in case of overlaps. Try out My Calendar #1 (729) for an easier problem related to this.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(log(n)) addition, O(1) get

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n) space

# Code
```
class CountIntervals {
    TreeMap<Integer,Integer> tm = new TreeMap<>();
    int c = 0;

    public CountIntervals() {}

    public void add(int start,int end){
        // nothing if not valid
        if(end < start)
            return;

        // check if out of the range of everything we have
        // condition 1: all intervals are greater than the new one
        // condition 2: if the next smallest interval ends before this one
        if(tm.floorKey(end) == null || tm.get(tm.floorKey(end)) < start){
            c += end-start+1;
            tm.put(start,end);
            return;
        }


        // If we're here, there's overlap
        int nS = tm.floorKey(end);
        int nE = tm.get(tm.floorKey(end));

        // if we cant add anything in because this interval encapsulates it
        if(start >= nS && end <= nE)
            return;

        add(start,nS-1);
        add(nE+1,end);
    }

    public int count() {
        return c;
    }
}

/**
 * Your CountIntervals object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * CountIntervals obj = new CountIntervals();
 * obj.add(left,right);
 * int param_2 = obj.count();
 */
