# Intuition
Basically we will need to merge intervals.

# Approach
0. maintain a treemap to store all intervals, and a variable count to store the number of covered integers
1. for each new interval to be added, find out an overlapping interval with smallest start;
2.  remove the overlapping interval from the treemap, subtract this interval's length from count;
3. merge the overlapping interval with the new interval, add it to the treemap, and add the length of the merged interval to count
4. repeat until there are no overlapping intervals

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(NlogN) because of treemap, the while loop itself costs O(N)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N)

# Code
```
class CountIntervals {

    int count;
    TreeMap<Integer, Integer> intervalMap;
    public CountIntervals() {
        this.count = 0;
        this.intervalMap = new TreeMap<>();
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        Integer floorStart = intervalMap.floorKey(left);
        if (floorStart == null) {
            floorStart = intervalMap.ceilingKey(left);
        } else if (floorStart != null && intervalMap.get(floorStart) < left) {
            floorStart = intervalMap.ceilingKey(left);
        }
        while (floorStart != null && (floorStart <= left && intervalMap.get(floorStart) >= left ||
                                      floorStart <= right && intervalMap.get(floorStart) >= right ||
                                      floorStart >= left && intervalMap.get(floorStart) <= right)) {
            int floorEnd = intervalMap.get(floorStart);
            intervalMap.remove(floorStart);
            count -= floorEnd - floorStart + 1;
            left = Math.min(floorStart, left);
            right = Math.max(floorEnd, right);
            floorStart = intervalMap.floorKey(left);
            if (floorStart == null) {
                floorStart = intervalMap.ceilingKey(left);
            } else if (floorStart != null && intervalMap.get(floorStart) < left) {
                floorStart = intervalMap.ceilingKey(left);
            }
        }

        intervalMap.put(left, right);
        count += right - left + 1;
    }

    public int count() {
        return count;
    }
}

```

