1. If no overlapping, directly add into the range map;
2. otherwise, enlarge the range, remove overlapping old ranges in the treeMap and  add new range into map. In the mean time, change the count which is a global variable.
```
    TreeMap<Integer, Integer>map;
    int count;
    public CountIntervals() {
        //key will be the range start point, value will be the range end point
        map = new TreeMap<>();
        count = 0;
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        Integer start = map.floorKey(left);
        Integer end = map.floorKey(right);

        //new interval can be added as a separate new one
        if(end != null && map.get(end) < left) {
            count += (right - left + 1);
            map.put(left, right);
        } else{
            //need delete overlapping range.
            //----  -----    ------- //orig
            //  ----------------   //new
            //to be removed
            //----  -----    ------- //all old that has overlapping with orig should be deleted.
            while(map.floorKey(right) != null && map.get(map.floorKey(right)) >= left) {
                int l = map.floorKey(right);
                int r = map.get(l);
                count -= (r - l + 1);
                map.remove(l);
                //enlarge the merged range, thus all overlapping (even partial ones) should be removed.
                left = Math.min(l, left);
                right = Math.max(r, right);
               }
        //replace start item with same range
        map.put(left, right);
        count += (right - left + 1);
        }
    }

    public int count() {
        return count;
    }
