All other solutions I saw here use a map, so I'm posting my solution using a regular list (which happens to be faster)

##### How this could be made even faster:
 - `Add` takes `O(logN)` time in average, but `O(N)` in worst case. __Can be modified to achieve `O(logN)` in the worst case__ also (a comment in the code suggests how this can be done), but that __might not be worth it__ for many test cases.
 - In some cases we call `RemoveRange` and then `Insert` to the same place. Those inserts could be avoided by removing 1 interval less and just changing its values.
 - Might be even faster with a `List<Range>` of structs (same memory footprint), to reduce number of calls to `Insert`.
 - The built-in `BinarySearch` is probably slower than it could be.
 - Some custom allocations strategy, with the goals of fast indexing/insertOne/removeRange. Most effort but also most theoretical performance gain, since 99% of *extra work* comes from moving memory around.


<small>note: the funky comments are just my visual aid, not meant to be explained</small>

```
public class CountIntervals {
    List<int> intervals = new List<int>(); // LR  LR  LR
    int count;

    public void Add(int left, int right)
    {
      // l is index of the [left] of the range smaller than us (can be -2)
      int l = intervals.BinarySearch(left);
      //  L R L R
      //  *^^^
      if (l < 0)
        l = ~l - 1;
      l -= l & 1; // move from R to its L

      // r is the index of the [left] of the range bigger than us (can be Length)
      int r = intervals.BinarySearch(right);
      //  L R L R
      //     ^*^^
      if (r < 0)
        r = ~r;
      r -= r & 1; // move from R to its L

      // L  R
      //  <>
      if (l==r)
        return; // overlapping a single range

      // L  R   L  R   L  R   L  R
      // l    < ****   **** > r
      for (int i = l + 2; i < r; i += 2)
        count -= intervals[i + 1] - intervals[i] + 1;
      // could avoid O(n) here, by saving an accumulatedCount per interval
      // but this O(n) operation is rare because it makes the N ranges collapse back into 1
      // so I'll leave it be

      bool mergeToLeft = l >= 0 && left <= intervals[l + 1] + 1;
      bool mergeToRight = r < intervals.Count && right >= intervals[r] - 1;
      if (mergeToLeft && mergeToRight)
      {
        // L  R   L  R   L  R   L  R
        //    x*<*x**x***x**x*>*x
        count += intervals[r] - intervals[l + 1] - 1;
        intervals.RemoveRange(l + 1, r - l);
        return;
      }
      if (mergeToLeft)
      {
        // L  R   L  R   L  R   L  R
        //  <  ***************>
        count += right - intervals[l + 1];
        intervals[l + 1] = right;
      }
      if (mergeToRight)
      {
        // L  R   L  R   L  R   L  R
        //      <***************  >
        count += intervals[r] - left;
        intervals[r] = left;
      }
      // L  R   L  R   L  R   L  R
      // l      x  x   x  x   r
      int del = r - l - 2;
      if (del > 0)
        intervals.RemoveRange(l + 2, del); // r is wrong now, dont use it any more
      if (!mergeToLeft && !mergeToRight)
      {
        intervals.Insert(l + 2, left);
        intervals.Insert(l + 3, right);
        count += right - left + 1;
      }
    }

    public int Count()
    {
      return count;
    }
}
```

