solutions.content:
We use a TreeMap to save non-overlapping intervals, and keep tracking of the count of integers in the TreeMap.
TreeMap enable us to find the closest intervals in the left and right hand side.
We resolve the overlap issue in the ```add()```.

ie: 
When adding [3, 11] into [2, 4], [5, 6], [7, 9], [9, 18]
1. in the left, [3, 11] overlaps with [2, 4]. We can remove [2, 4] (and adjust the ```cnt``` accordingly), and change the attempting one to [2, 11]
2. In the right, [2, 11] overlaps with [5, 6], [7, 9], [9, 18]. We can remove them all (and adjust the ```cnt``` accordingly) and and change the attempting one to [2, 18]
3. add [2, 18] and it's cnt.
```
class CountIntervals {
    TreeMap<Integer, Integer> tmap; // left, length
    int cnt;

    public CountIntervals() {
        tmap = new TreeMap<>();
        cnt = 0;
    }

    public void add(int left, int right) {
        // check the closest one in the left
        Integer floorKey = tmap.floorKey(left);
        if (floorKey != null) {
            // check if overlap
            int floorLength = tmap.get(floorKey);
            if (floorKey + floorLength - 1 >= right) {
                /*
				completely covered by the existing one
				ie:  adding [3, 5] into [2, 6]
				not need to do anything 
				*/
                return;
            }

            if (floorKey + floorLength - 1 >= left) {
			/*
			ie: adding [3, 6] to [2, 5]
			then we remove existing [2, 5]
			and combine it into the attemping one 
			so now we are attempting [2, 6] with no overlaping in the left side
			*/
                tmap.remove(floorKey);
                left = floorKey;
                cnt -= floorLength;
            }
        }

        // check the closet one in the right side
        Integer ceilingKey = tmap.ceilingKey(left);
        if (ceilingKey == null || ceilingKey > right) {
			/*
			we have not overlaping with the nearest right interval.
			Just add the attempted one and we are done
			*/
            tmap.put(left, right - left + 1);
            cnt += right - left + 1;
            return;
        }
        int ceilLength = tmap.get(ceilingKey);
        while(ceilingKey + ceilLength - 1 <= right) {
			/*
			the closest one in the right side is completely covered by the attempted interval
			ie: adding [3, 6] to [4, 5]
			then we remove [4, 5]
			and check the next closest one
			*/
            tmap.remove(ceilingKey);
            cnt -= ceilLength;
            ceilingKey = tmap.ceilingKey(left);
            if (ceilingKey == null || ceilingKey > right) {
			// if no overlap, save and return
                tmap.put(left, right - left + 1);
                cnt += right - left + 1;
                return;
            }
            ceilLength = tmap.get(ceilingKey);
        }
		/*
		when we reach this point, we have parcially overlap with the next one
		ie: adding [3, 6] into [5, 7]
		then we remove [5, 7]
		and change to attampted one to [3, 7]
		*/
        tmap.remove(ceilingKey);
        cnt -= ceilLength;
        tmap.put(left, ceilingKey + ceilLength - left);
        cnt += ceilingKey + ceilLength - left;
    }

    public int count() {
        return cnt;
    }
}
```

