# Intuition
Because of the way the seats are populated, it makes sense to model this as a list of "gaps" in the seats, where each gap is a sequence of empty seats that span over an arbitrary number of rows. A gap could start on any seat within the starting row, but would always end on the last seat in the end row.

# Approach
A class was implemented to represent a gap, with methods to fill the gap, and split into two where required.

Since the collection of gaps is always accessed and modified sequentially, it made sense to use a LinkedList of gaps.

The scatter method then iterates over the collection of gaps and fills in from the bottom. This never requires splitting a gap into two.

The gather method iterates over the collection of gaps until it finds one that can accommodate the required number of seats. Depending on the current state of the gaps, this may require splitting a gap into two.

# Complexity
g = number of gaps, where 1 <= g <= n
(where n is the number of rows)
- Time complexity: $$O(g)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(g)$$

