# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I have used the property that, for any two rows which are not totally empty, the total number of available seats  in those rows must be less than the total number of seats in a row. 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The above intuition implies:
- In *gather*, if in any occupied row, the number of filled seats is less than the number of seats required to  be reserved, then we can skip the search to the first empty row. This helps reduce the time required by the search.
- In *scatter*, the max possible available seats in $\mathcal{L}$ seats which are neither completely empty, nor completely full is $ m*\lceil\frac{\mathcal{L}}{2}\rceil$.

Using above two optimizations, unordered search is used for each row, after the one that has been marked completely filled.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $\mathcal{O}(n)$ (worst case)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $\mathcal{O}(n)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


